Boil a large #pot{} of salted @water{to taste} for the pasta.

When boiling, add the @dried linguine{180%grams} to the water and bring back to the boil.

Cook until softened, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pot (off the heat). Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and stir through to prevent sticking.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(grated using a garlic press or box grater).

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

== Beef ==

Place a large #pan{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once the pan is hot, fry the @Irish beef strips{250%grams} shifting as they colour, until cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw meat and its packaging. Meat is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Once browned, remove from the pan and set aside.

Return the pan to medium-high heat.

== Sauce ==

Add the @red wine jus{1%sachet}, @beef stock{1%sachet}, @passata{1%pack}, @dried chilli flakes{1%sachet}, garlic, @water{100%ml} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} (double both for 4p) to the pan.

> Use less chilli flakes if you don't like spice.

Bring to a boil then reduce to a simmer.

Cook, stirring occasionally, until thickened, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} and @sugar{to taste}. Stir through a knob of @butter{to taste}. Add a splash of water if the sauce is too thick.

Before serving, toss pasta and beef through the sauce.

== To Serve ==

Share the beef arrabbiata between bowls.

Finish with a sprinkling of @grated cheese{50%grams}.